      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Construct stiffness QoI comparison — non-cannulated 7.5 mm",
      "description": "FEA-predicted construct stiffness was compared to the mean experimental stiffness from N=11 specimens tested across two independent laboratories under ASTM F1717 static compression-bending. The ensemble of three FEA models (FDA implicit solver, Ansys Mechanical, DePuy Synthes in-house code) yielded a mean predicted stiffness of 142.3 N/mm against an experimental mean of 138.7 N/mm (SD 6.2 N/mm). The percentage difference was 2.6%, well within the pre-specified 10% acceptance bound. The validation uncertainty metric E/uval was computed as 0.81, satisfying the E/uval < 1.96 criterion. Experimental testing was conducted at FDA CDRH biomechanics laboratory (primary) and DePuy Synthes R&D laboratory (secondary) using calibrated Instron 8874 biaxial test frames; load-cell calibration certificates and fixture geometry logs are archived in the project data repository. All three FEA solvers used identical mesh topology (hexahedral-dominant, ~180 000 elements), material property assignments sourced from literature-validated titanium alloy data (Ti-6Al-4V, E=114 GPa), and boundary conditions replicating the ASTM F1717 fixture geometry. The detailed simulation execution records, including solver version, hardware platform, run timestamps, and convergence logs, are documented in the project simulation notebook and are considered sufficient to trace the provenance of this result.",
